[Student "S"]
{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \HK. West plays the \H6.

Winners:   \S=3  \H=1  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 8

You just need one more winner and it could come from the \D suit if it happens to split 3-3. But you have another possibility. Suppose you let East hold the first trick and he decides to play another \H? You would have two \H winners.

This isn't a true hold-up play although it does look like one. This play has the rather fancy name of Bath Coup, (named from Bath, England). Presumably East has led from \H K Q 10 9 5 and West has played his singleton \H6. If East realizes that West has played his lowest card he will take that as a discouraging signal and will play a different suit. So you throw out your \H7 rather than the \H3. Now East may think that West is encouraging him to continue, just what you want.

Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.

I sure hope that when you play this hand East falls for your Bath Coup.

Because if he doesn't you're going to have to end-play him.

Do you see how that might happen?}
[Play "W"]HK

